hf_hf1.text: Holmes deduces that a child's cruel disposition may come from their parents, indicating a connection between parental behavior and child character.

hf_hf2.text: Holmes and Watson arrive at the Copper Beeches at seven o'clock to investigate a case involving a missing child.

hf_hf3.text: Holmes discovers that a prisoner has escaped through an open skylight, indicating a clever plan by the captor.

hf_hf4.text: A fat man appears at the door with a heavy stick, indicating a confrontation between him and Holmes.

hf_hf5.text: A hound is unleashed, leading to a violent encounter where it attacks Mr. Rucastle, who is described as elderly and in distress.

hf_hf6.text: Mrs. Toller reveals that Miss Alice was unhappy at home and had rights by will that were ignored by her father, Mr. Rucastle.

hf_hf7.text: Mr. Fowler, who was persistent in his pursuit of Miss Alice, is mentioned as having a significant role in the events surrounding her imprisonment.

hf_hf8.text: Mr. Fowler and Miss Rucastle were married in Southampton the day after their flight, indicating a resolution to their predicament.

hf_hf9.text: Miss Violet Hunter becomes the head of a private school at Walsall, suggesting her successful transition after the events of the case.

hf_hf10.text: Holmes reflects on the isolation of the countryside and the potential for crime in rural areas, contrasting it with urban environments.

hf_hf11.text: The banker’s niece, Mary, left a note and deserted him.

hf_hf12.text: Holmes received a cheque for £4000 from the banker.

hf_hf13.text: Holmes revealed that Sir George Burnwell and Mary fled together.

hf_hf14.text: Arthur saw Mary with the coronet and followed her.

hf_hf15.text: Holmes found blood drops in the snow during his investigation.

hf_hf16.text: Holmes tracked footprints in the snow to solve the case.

hf_hf17.text: Holmes confronted Sir George Burnwell about the stolen gems.

hf_hf18.text: The banker thanked Holmes for saving him from scandal.

hf_hf19.text: Mary expressed her belief in Arthur's innocence and urged Mr. Holder to reconsider his actions.

hf_hf20.text: Holmes and Mr. Holder traveled to Streatham to investigate the case further.

hf_hf_1.text: A young lady was waiting at a station for her companions, having engaged a sitting-room and prepared lunch.

hf_hf_2.text: The young lady expressed her gratitude for the advice she was about to receive regarding her situation with Mr. Rucastle.

hf_hf_3.text: Mr. Rucastle drove the young lady to the Copper Beeches, a large house situated near the Southampton high road.

hf_hf_4.text: The young lady described Mr. Rucastle's wife as a silent, pale-faced woman, much younger than him, and noted their marriage lasted about seven years.

hf_hf_5.text: The daughter of Mr. Rucastle from his first marriage has gone to Philadelphia due to her aversion to her stepmother.

hf_hf_6.text: The young lady observed that Mrs. Rucastle was devoted to her husband and child, despite having a secret sorrow.

hf_hf_7.text: The young lady noted the unpleasant conduct of the servants, particularly Toller, who was often drunk.

hf_hf_8.text: Mr. Rucastle asked the young lady to change into an electric-blue dress, which had been laid out for her.

hf_hf_9.text: The young lady found a peculiar blue dress that had been worn before and fit her perfectly.

hf_hf_10.text: The young lady observed a man in a grey suit standing in the Southampton Road, looking in her direction.

hf_hf_11.text: Mrs. Rucastle instructed the young lady to wave the man away, indicating he was an impertinent fellow.

hf_hf_12.text: The young lady discovered her hair in a locked drawer, identical to the hair she had cut off in London.

hf_hf_13.text: Mr. Rucastle appeared angry when he locked a door leading to a part of the house that was not inhabited.

hf_hf_14.text: The young lady observed that the locked door corresponded with a shuttered window, indicating something was hidden inside.

hf_hf_15.text: The young lady felt a sense of duty to investigate the locked room, believing it might hold important secrets.

hf_hf_16.text: The young lady encountered Mr. Rucastle after trying to enter the locked room, who warned her against doing so.

hf_hf_17.text: The young lady decided to send a wire to Mr. Holmes for advice after feeling frightened in the house.

hf_hf_18.text: Mr. Holmes planned to visit the Copper Beeches at seven o'clock to investigate the situation further.

axes.name: Emotion vs. Logic
axes.description: This axis represents the tension between emotional engagement and logical reasoning, highlighting the characters' approaches to situations.

bins.label: Emotionally Driven
bins.description: Characters in this bin prioritize emotional connections and personal relationships over logical reasoning.
prototypes: Irene Adler's influence on Holmes
Watson's concern for Holmes' well-being
The King's desperation for love

bins.label: Balanced Approach
bins.description: Characters exhibit a mix of emotional engagement and logical reasoning, often weighing both aspects in their decisions.
prototypes: Holmes' admiration for Adler's intellect
Watson's support for Holmes while maintaining his own life
The King's logical need to retrieve the photograph

bins.label: Logically Driven
bins.description: Characters in this bin rely heavily on logic and reasoning, often dismissing emotional considerations.
prototypes: Holmes' cold deduction methods
The King's initial reluctance to admit feelings
Holmes' focus on facts over emotions

bins.label: Conflict of Interests
bins.description: Characters face dilemmas where emotional desires conflict with logical necessities, leading to tension.
prototypes: The King's love vs. his royal duties
Holmes' emotional struggle with Adler's impact
Watson's loyalty to Holmes vs. his own life

bins.label: Emotional Detachment
bins.description: Characters exhibit a strong detachment from emotions, often prioritizing logic to the point of neglecting personal connections.
prototypes: Holmes' dismissal of romantic feelings
The King's initial coldness towards his situation
Holmes' view of emotions as distractions

bins.label: Emotional Manipulation
bins.description: Characters use emotional appeals or manipulations to achieve their goals, often leading to unexpected outcomes.
prototypes: Adler's clever use of her charm
The King's reliance on emotional leverage
Holmes' strategic emotional insights

axes.name: Social Status
axes.description: This axis reflects the social hierarchy and status of characters, from common individuals to nobility, influencing their interactions and motivations.

bins.label: Commoners
bins.description: Characters from the lower social strata, often depicted as struggling or striving for betterment.
prototypes: A humble shopkeeper trying to make ends meet.
A laborer dreaming of a better life.
A servant navigating the complexities of their employer's world.

bins.label: Middle Class
bins.description: Individuals with moderate wealth and social standing, often depicted as aspiring to higher status.
prototypes: A doctor with a growing practice.
A teacher advocating for social change.
A merchant seeking respectability.

bins.label: Upper Middle Class
bins.description: Characters who enjoy a comfortable lifestyle, often involved in social or political issues.
prototypes: A lawyer defending the rights of the underprivileged.
A philanthropist funding local charities.
A journalist exposing corruption.

bins.label: Nobility
bins.description: Members of the aristocracy, often depicted as having significant power and influence.
prototypes: A duke with a troubled past.
A countess navigating court politics.
A baron with a secret agenda.

bins.label: Royalty
bins.description: Characters of the highest social rank, often facing unique challenges due to their status.
prototypes: A king torn between duty and desire.
A queen fighting for her legacy.
A prince caught in a scandal.

bins.label: Outcasts
bins.description: Characters who exist outside the traditional social hierarchy, often marginalized or misunderstood.
prototypes: An artist struggling for recognition.
A revolutionary challenging the status quo.
A detective operating on the fringes of society.

axes.name: Action vs. Inaction
axes.description: This axis measures the degree of activity or passivity exhibited by characters, indicating their engagement in events versus their tendency to observe.

bins.label: Active Engagement
bins.description: Characters exhibit high levels of activity and involvement in events, taking decisive actions.
prototypes: Holmes actively deduces clues.
Watson rushes to assist Holmes.
The King seeks Holmes' help urgently.

bins.label: Observational Passivity
bins.description: Characters observe situations without intervening, often reflecting on events rather than acting.
prototypes: Watson watches Holmes work.
The narrator reflects on Holmes' methods.
Characters discuss events without taking action.

bins.label: Strategic Planning
bins.description: Characters engage in careful planning and strategizing before taking action.
prototypes: Holmes devises a plan to retrieve the photograph.
The King outlines his concerns about the scandal.
Holmes prepares for the confrontation with criminals.

bins.label: Delayed Action
bins.description: Characters hesitate or delay their actions, often due to uncertainty or fear.
prototypes: Holmes waits for the right moment to act.
Watson hesitates before intervening.
The King fears the consequences of his past.

bins.label: Reactive Response
bins.description: Characters respond to events as they unfold, often in a reactive manner rather than proactive.
prototypes: Holmes reacts to unexpected developments.
Watson responds to Holmes' cues.
The King reacts to Irene's threats.

bins.label: Inaction Due to Fear
bins.description: Characters refrain from acting due to fear of consequences or uncertainty about the outcome.
prototypes: The King fears the scandal's impact.
Watson worries about Holmes' safety.
Holmes considers the risks of his plans.

axes.name: Mystery Depth
axes.description: This axis gauges the complexity and depth of the mysteries presented, from simple puzzles to intricate plots involving significant stakes.

bins.label: Simple Mysteries
bins.description: These involve straightforward puzzles or situations with clear resolutions and minimal stakes.
prototypes: A missing item found in plain sight.
A simple misunderstanding resolved quickly.
A character's secret easily uncovered.

bins.label: Moderate Intrigues
bins.description: These feature more complex scenarios with multiple characters and some level of deception or hidden motives.
prototypes: A love triangle with a hidden letter.
A theft that involves a clever ruse.
A character's dual identity revealed.

bins.label: Complex Conspiracies
bins.description: These involve intricate plots with significant stakes, often including multiple layers of deception and high tension.
prototypes: A royal scandal threatening a kingdom.
A heist involving elaborate planning.
A character's past coming back to haunt them.

bins.label: High-Stakes Dilemmas
bins.description: These present moral or ethical challenges that could have serious consequences for the characters involved.
prototypes: A choice between loyalty and justice.
A secret that could ruin a reputation.
A decision that could alter the course of history.

bins.label: Psychological Games
bins.description: These delve into the minds of characters, exploring their motivations and the psychological impact of their actions.
prototypes: A character manipulating another for personal gain.
A mind game that leads to unexpected outcomes.
A confrontation that reveals deep-seated fears.

bins.label: Twisted Revelations
bins.description: These involve shocking twists that change the understanding of the entire narrative, often revealing hidden truths.
prototypes: The true villain is revealed to be a trusted ally.
A character's identity is not what it seems.
A seemingly unrelated event ties everything together.

axes.name: Time Period
axes.description: This axis indicates the temporal setting of events, ranging from past recollections to present actions, influencing character development and plot progression.

bins.label: Historical Past
bins.description: Events and character developments rooted in historical contexts, often reflecting societal norms and values of the time.
prototypes: Victorian England's societal expectations
The impact of the Industrial Revolution
Colonial influences on character motivations

bins.label: Recent Past
bins.description: Events that occurred shortly before the present narrative, shaping characters' current situations and relationships.
prototypes: Watson's marriage affecting his friendship with Holmes
Holmes' recent cases influencing his current demeanor
Past encounters with Irene Adler impacting the King's actions

bins.label: Present Actions
bins.description: Current events and decisions that drive the plot forward, showcasing characters' immediate motivations and conflicts.
prototypes: Holmes deducing clues in real-time
The King's urgent need to retrieve the photograph
Watson's involvement in Holmes' latest case

bins.label: Future Implications
bins.description: Foreshadowing events that hint at potential outcomes and character arcs, often creating suspense and anticipation.
prototypes: The King's impending marriage and its stakes
Irene Adler's potential actions with the photograph
Holmes' reflections on the consequences of his deductions

bins.label: Timeless Themes
bins.description: Universal themes that transcend specific time periods, reflecting enduring human experiences and emotions.
prototypes: Love and betrayal in relationships
The quest for identity and self-understanding
The struggle between duty and personal desire
